    "summary": "Washington is broadly protective of transgender rights: a 2023 shield law (HB 1469) blocks cooperation with out-of-state investigations of gender-affirming care, there are no bans or penalties on treatment, and public or private insurance must cover that care.  Residents can self-attest to update birth certificates and driver licences, including an “X” marker, and the state’s civil-rights law bars gender-identity discrimination in employment, housing, and public accommodations.  Hate-crime statutes expressly protect gender identity and the state has banned the trans-panic defense, though prison housing decisions remain case-by-case.  Schools must allow trans students access to restrooms and sports teams that match their gender identity, but there is no explicit statewide law against forced outing of students.  Washington also prohibits discrimination in adoption and foster care, yet comprehensive violence data for 2023-24 are not yet published.",
